body:
While writing up a set of instructions for end users, I noticed that podman suggests different setup/configuration branches for Windows/MacOS than for Linux. While this makes sense from an architectural perspective (Linux doesn't need a Linux VM), it gets exposed as extra branching logic that is then required to be implemented by third-party integrations.

What would be great is being able to run the exact same set of instructions across all platforms to produce the same results. For example, on Linux:

``` bash
podman --fail-with "Skipping initialization (not needed)." machine init
podman --fail-with "Skipping virtual machine start-up (not needed)." machine start
podman load --quiet -i build/typesetter.tar.gz
podman run --network=host --rm -it typesetter /bin/sh --login -c "/usr/bin/ls"
```

Pie-in-the sky, would be a single command that blends all this functionality and "just works" across all platforms while taking into consideration the knowledge of podman's current state. That is:

``` bash
podman \
  --if-needed machine init \
  --if-needed machine start \
  --if-needed load -i build/typesetter.tar.gz --then \
  run --network=host --rm -it typesetter /bin/sh --login -c "ls"
```

That would initialize and start the VM on Windows/MacOS (or whatever other OS needs it) if necessary, load the image if it hasn't already been loaded, then run the given command against the container.

At present, my code includes:

``` java
  @Override
  public void start() throws FileNotFoundException {
    assert !IS_OS_LINUX;

    machine( "init" );
    machine( "start" );
  }

  private void machine( final String option ) throws FileNotFoundException {
    run( "machine", option );
  }

  private void run( final String... args ) throws FileNotFoundException {
    try {
      final var exe = CONTAINER.locate();
      final var path = exe.orElseThrow();
      final var commands = new LinkedList<String>();
      commands.add( path.toAbsolutePath().toString() );
      commands.addAll( Arrays.asList( args ) );

      final var builder = new ProcessBuilder( commands );
      final var process = builder.start();

      // etc.
      // process.getOutputStream();
    } catch( final Exception ex ) {
      throw new FileNotFoundException( CONTAINER.toString() );
    }
  }
```

The line that troubles me the most is `assert !IS_OS_LINUX;` because it means podman's operating system requirements have leaked into my software. The other leak is in creating the installation wizard, which needs to add an additional panel, but only for Windows/MacOS (non-Linux?) users:

``` java
    if( !SystemUtils.IS_OS_LINUX ) {
      panes.add( createContainerInitializationPanel() );
    }
```

I'm aware that I could opt to simply run the commands and if they fail on Linux, ignore it, and as they run on Windows/MacOS, let them finish in the background. That wouldn't give a great experience because (a) if something goes wrong, I'd still need to pop a panel with the error message; and (b) init/start takes a while, so it's nice to give users a status update showing what's happening.

comments.body:
> It would be better to have a separate boolean, and then have it default to true on Windows/macOS and to false when running on Linux ?

The wizard panels have similar logic to that:

``` java
  private WizardPane[] wizardPanes() {
    final var panes = new LinkedList<WizardPane>();

    panes.add( createIntroductionPane() );

    if( IS_OS_WINDOWS ) {
      panes.add( createContainerDownloadPanelWindows() );
      panes.add( createContainerInstallPanelWindows() );
    }
    else if( IS_OS_UNIX ) {
      panes.add( createContainerInstallPanelUnix() );
    }
    else {
      panes.add( createContainerInstallPanelUniversal() );
    }

    if( !IS_OS_LINUX ) {
      panes.add( createContainerInitializationPanel() );
    }

    panes.add( createTypesetterImageDownloadPanel() );

    return panes.toArray( WizardPane[]::new );
  }
```

As per the topic of this ticket, my preference would be to write the following, without the `!IS_OS_LINUX` conditional:

``` java
    panes.add( createContainerInitializationPanel() );
    panes.add( createTypesetterImageDownloadPanel() );
```

With that in mind, ultimately, I'd rather not have to force any of these panels onto end users if there was a way to avoid it that'd still let users know what was happening and whether any show-stopper errors (that require user intervention) were encountered. Qué será, será.
